The problem, as in almost everything about Tajikistan, is that motivated decision-makers can get what they want regardless of what the law says. For violations of the new Law, amnesty is unavailable and antenatal detention is available. Nor does article 149 concede that abortion must be performed by a doctor or in a hospital. If it is a done by a midwife, the sentence remains as under the old law and the offence is treated as negligence. The law does make a concession, however in Article 148 (3) which states:

‘Abortions strictly prohibited in the following cases: 
 a) . . 
 d) on a decision of a treating physician;

So, it may be better advised that any abortion be done in compliance with article 148 – even if it appears unwanted, medical practitioners will (hopefully) fear that the additional charge of abortion being done by a person other than that implanting the contraceptive against the instruction of a physician and the prescribed form of the birth control will lead to prosecution for prescribing contraceptives or implants.

Murman Shermatov

Sources used in this article: Network-M, ‘Tajik Law Goes Too Far’ online (23 March 2017) <https://www.network-m.ru/news/tadzhikistan/zak
